,Recommended,329130,14631492,"Posted: 24 February, 2015",all,Elate,"If you like Battleships Forever or Captain Forever, this game is for you. (They're both freeware so go try them if you're interested in this.) It takes the concepts of both, and throws in a bit of Starsector (namely the fleet mechanics) for good measure to make a game I've poured hours into already. (As of writing, I've played it for 10.8 hours. I bought it yesterday.)While some have also compared it to Gimbal, I'd say only at the very start. The comparison starts losing ground once you get the bigger ships.Where this stands out is the.. well, game. BF and CF are both fun for a short play, but don't have many backing gameplay mechanics. Reassembly gives you economies, waring fations, fleet control and quite a bit of variety (Though I'd like to see mod support in the future for even more pieces/factions). Each faction also plays differently in various ways, for example, one can plant and grow their own resources, but seem to be lacking in firepower, another has literal nukes, but no shields, and so on, it forces a change in tactics when it comes to ship design that keeps things fresh. With all that in mind, it's still a sandbox, outside of the tutorial, what you do is purely up to you with zero guidance, I personally like that, some might not.It should also be noted it seems to run superbly. I have a fairly powerful machine, but any game with 1000s of ships/particles will slow it down some. This doesn't, I've had fleets of hundreds of ships facing off against each other, and it has stayed at a stable 60fps.All in all, one of the best games I've purchased in a very long time.EDIT: Apparently mod support is already somewhat in the game. I got ahead of myself."
,Recommended,329130,14822436,"Posted: 10 March, 2015",all,x3n0ph0b3,"In my opinion, this is the best purchase I've made all year.Synopsis:You fly ships and blow things up, exploring new sectors and conquering the universe. You collect resources.  You upgrade your blueprints and your ""power level"" to build bigger, better ships.Eventually you can build ""factories"" on your ships, which allow your ships to produce even more ships. These ships become part of your ""fleet"", allowing you to get into bigger, better fights.Upgrades are permanent. Possibilities are almost endless.What I love:1) Few restrictions are imposed on designs. Making ships is a blast. Learn the shortcuts.2) Factions and weapons vary well. Each has strengths and flaws. There is no magic bullet.3) The learning curve to designing ships is rewarding. You will quickly discover what doesn't work.4) Making mistakes is okay. Your flagship is basically free. You can recover from losses easily.5) Fights are exciting, managing your fleet is addictive. This game is fun for me.6) The objectives aren't super important. My goal is to conquer the universe.Cons, which I hope to explain away:1) The music became repetitive. I replaced it with my own, no big deal.2) The building interface is tricky at first. Learn the shortcuts.3) Controlling ships is tricky at first. Don't neglect propulsion in all directions.4) Rarely, I will get ""stuck"" on things on collision. It may be a bug, but I try not to hit things.5) [Related] an ""impending collision indicator"" would be awesome. Seriously.6) I feel like dismantling ships you don't want for money/scrap should be a thing you can do.7) I hate tutorial popups.Give me a help window to explain the controls in full, I'll refer to it as needed.Don't interrupt me while I'm destroying the universe.This problem is a minor annoyance at the beginning of a new campaign.I really feel like this game outshines. It is definitely worth the $15 for me."
