76561198029055397,Recommended,329130,28855463,"Posted: 30 December, 2016",all,Wilphart,"This game is nearly perfect.  If there were a multi-player arena where players could go against other players in a duel or FFA, then it would be perfect.First of all, it captures the the ship-building and physics of Astro Battle(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astro_Battle), but... better.  More parts, more customization, and factions with different techs that support different playstyles.  It's more forgiving to newbs too - each individual thruster doesn't need to be keyed for steering - the computer takes care of that.  But Astro Battle was only PVP, and you couldn't play it when nobody else was online.But it also captures the mayhem of a giant 2D dogfight the way Hellfighter did(http://www.dracova.com/hellfighter/).  Both Astro Battle & Hellfighter were fun, but neither lived up to its potential.  I think they're both abandoned now, but I still have the memories.  This gives you an AI to fight with lots of ships, but lets you customize yours and potentially every one in your fleet.  Best of both worlds.And you can artistically design your ships, colors, space stations to shape the world.  In that regard, it reminds me a lot of Spore from EA games, only this is is combat-oriented.  Spore was incredibly fun in the early stages, but lost out when you got to the galaxy stage - the single fleet that capped out at half  a dozen was the only thing making the economy go, and the galaxy quickly became too big for your little fleet.  In Reassembly, every ship has an independent captain and the ""economy"" works for each individual.  You don't need to babysit your empire, so it's not tedious - and there's no cap to the fleet you can have, so battles are FUN.And there is a decent AI to play against.  Not as good as PvP in some ways, but better in other ways.  The AI lets you test your own designs against - your own designs, for example.  And you can fight the AI-controlled blueprints that were designed from other players.  It's almost as good as facing off with other players.  There is a tournament mode that lets you upload different ships/fleets and then watch the magic.And finally, there is a neat little environment where space vegetation and debris from other ships can be collected as resources to build other ships from factories, and you can get a fleet that can maintain itself and increase it's numbers based on strategic settlements and/or battle victories.The different factions make for diverse opponents, and once you defeat a battleship from another faction, they become playable if you want to play as another race.  And the biggest challenges are fleets from successful players - or the AI playing with custom ships designed by players, anyway.Everything about the interface is user-friendly, but not cumbersome.  The designers did it right - including lots of shortcuts in the ship designer to make building big things easier.  You can tell they are perfectionists.  But they also made it mod-friendly in case you have a different version of perfection.  I can't say enough good things about it."
,Recommended,329130,30258519,Posted: 1 March,all,Sixela963,"I got this game a veeeeeery long time ago (it was still in early access if I remember well), and it is still by far my favorite once-in-a-while game. When I'm not sure what to do, I launch Reassembly and play for a perfectly undetermined amount of time.Reassembly is the perfect relaxation game. The music is both calm and upbeat, making the transitions between travelling, gathering and fighting almost seemless. Vector graphics also help to the surreal feel, and they allow the game to run very smoothly on most computers (as long as you keep away from the damn spiky plants, spamming projectiles until your computer fries). Fighting is also a spam-festival, but somehow keeps your game running good (and there is never FPS drop: only a physical simulation slowdown), and it is just exciting enough to be fun without making you hyper-active like playing Quake on accelerated speed after injection of pure Montain Dew essence. Death happens a lot, but isn't too punishing most of the time, and you usually tell yourself ""oh, well"" and keep going. Building is complex enough to make you activate a few brain cells without frying them, and permissive enough to allow for some beautifully shaped motherships,or if you are like me, spamming of pulse lasers to make an one-shot cube. Speaking of absurd powerful weapons, The tech system (a.k.a factions, unlocking weapons and upgrading your ship) is diverse and smooth enough to keep you going for quite some time.My personnal recommandation is to spam the same mid or end-tier weapon to make your gunships, except for the tinkrel (purple guys) able to make their own weapons: here just make a fat♥♥♥♥♥death-pouring valve, it's hilarious. And of course never forget the anti-missile cannons.My personnal favourite faction is the Red, because the lack of shields (hardest faction, by the way) forces you in making a swarm of well-designed ships, usually quite cheap and fast to produce. Unless you try to attack a ridiculous player-made gunship, few fleets can compete with a 100 ships army.The only complain I have is the lack of true multiplayer: you can see other player-made fleets in your world (agents), but that's it.Otherwise, I highly recommend getting this game."
