,Recommended,329130,30052024,Posted: 19 February,all,IIIStrife,"So, after the time I've spent playing this game, I can say it's definitely fun, but is it fun enough that you'll want to 100% it and get every achievement?Nah. After 63 hours, sure, I've gotten my money's worth, but sadly all spent in each race, and sadly, I no longer am even vaguely interested in it.Don't get me wrong, it's a good game, it's just... not one I can say is a great one. Whether this be due to the Dev's apparent abandonment of this game, I can say this for sure.If you wanna play for 20 hours in an interesting title, then pickit up, but if you want something to play for a LONG time, longer than 63 hours, then don't pick this up.I Still play Quake 1, 2, Doom's every pre-3 version, Creeper Worlds 1-3, Master of Orion 2, and Diablo 1 and 2.Those games are older than this by anywhere between 1 year and 2 decades.You can buy all of them too.If you want modular ships, then go for it, otherwise... Ehhh. It's fun, but it has limitations, such as the whole universe and world not being constantly active, leading you to go to every place to clear it out yourself, rather than do it Sim Ant style, and build a fleet so powerful, that your allies jsut take everything over through sheer attrition.Other limitations include:- A VERY limited Tournament system, only allowing one fleet to engage another person's single fleet. Not one fleet from one save, or faction. One fleet PERIOD. Also you can't manually control ships either in PvP combat, so that's extremely lame.- No Co-op, which this game could badly use on the ""Conquer everything"" achievement, which requires you to have a ship in every quadrant, which.... good luck, there's over 2000 of the things and hte map only updates in proximity of another player, let alone triggers and moves normally. Going fast enough can make it painfully obvious, which is possible to do without any mods btw.- The 8000 Ship size limit is fine, but when you're grinding up to that point (which IS a grind with some factions, with others, it's just plain tedious in every way) the imagination tends to run wild with about a dozen or more ideas that aren't possible without using mods.- Agents (user-submitted fleets controlled by AI only) sometimes don't spawn correctly and you gotta regen your world to get them to spawn correctly. This doesn't stop Agents from killing stations though, since, if Agents fought any of MY stations, none of them would survive, especially with my terran faction that abuses missiles (Hint: Lasers eventually do nothing)- Some weapons are just straight-up overpowered if spammed, whilst other weapons are jsut pretty much useless. Case and Point: Photon Lances, Missiles and Drones are 3 overpowered-when-spammed weapons. Everything literally pales in comparison. Missiles can overpowerd and overwhelm literally everything.- Railguns are useless for the most part, which is sad because Railguns are 50 times more powerful than any lasers, missiles (save for nukes) or fighter/bomber in any amounts irl. Hint: Because Railguns are literally matter shot at the speed of light, or atleast faster than the speed of sound, which is still deadly on that level.- AI doesn't redesign ships to counter your powerful warships, as a result, you can eventually design ships that nothing has an answer for, at which point the game's no longer challenging, which wears out the fun pretty quickly after a point. Case and Point: Terran Ships literally made up of a couple of shield generators, and literally a hundred missile launchers.- You can't stop the game from Auto-pausing without pausing, then unpausing as you immediately tab out. Reason why you'd want to do this: You may have a ship that revolves around puking out space stations for the purpose of just flooding the universe with stations that can also slowly puke out ships on it's own.The game's more or less a 7/10. Good, but not great. Plenty of flaws."
