,Recommended,329130,14603963,"Posted: 22 February, 2015",all,nixx0r,"tl;dr Spore meets SubSpace (aka Continuum), 8/10. Remember SubSpace? Need I say more? I do? Okay.As others have said, this game is extremely addictive. In a good way. The ship editor in itself is hours of lego-style building fun, but add to that a really immersive single-player world with player-made ships and you have a game that is both simple and compelling at the same time.Definitely worth the money, tons of replayability. Summarizing my experience as follows:Pros:- Great physics / destructable levels, and combat is super fun.- Awesome soundtrack.- World is huge but not infinite. That's a good thing for a space game.- Building ships is surprisingly fun. I'm not usually the type to want to buy a game then spend hours in an editor customizing things. The editor is very featureful and forgiving (undo, redo, copy paste), unlike many other in-game editors out there.- Sending your ship into a wormhole uploads your fleet into the ether so they can be run in other player games as the bad guys, Spore-style! In other words, tons of player-made content.- If you get sick of your world, fly into a wormhole and explore a parallel dimension instead.Cons:- Controls are a little quirky, especially on gamepads. Don't use a gamepad. Occasionally you'll find yourself slamming into an asteroid and getting completely stuck because the ""fly backwards"" key gets completely rotated and you and up flying into the asteroid and flailing around until you're killed by a passing enemy.- Ship editor is missing a MANUAL test flight option to get a sense of the maneuverability of the ship you spent an hour making.- Ship editor is missing important info about total mass / total thrust / total energy created which could help to approximate the above stuff. Only total resource capacity is listed-- everything else you have to calculate yourself.- NO MULTIPLAYER! The player-made content is fun in SP, but a game like this just begs for multiplayer.- Once you've maxed out points, Actual gameplay is 1-dimensional. Mostly consists of flying around and shooting everything you see-- or if you're like me and setup auto-fire, it's just flying around and letting the ship shoot everything for you. You can explore to find new bases, but that doesn't really give you anything.On the last two points, I wonder if I'm just misunderstanding some of the game dynamics, but it seems like unlocking bases is just there to occupy your time. I also don't really know if you can ever wipe out another faction. It would be great if:- You could watch bases expand over time, including size and number of ships, so you actually have more allies flying around. Ditto for enemies that go unchecked.- You could actually attack enemy bases and eventually wipe out factions. It would be awesome if each faction actually had a stronghold base you have to kill in order to wipe out an enemy.- There were new factions added over time, including to existing regions. Maybe I haven't played for long enough, but it seems like the same factions just exist in perpetuity.There it is. Lots of cons because the pros seem obvious to me. It's damn fun! It could be even better if the above things were addressed."
