76561198001357544,Recommended,329130,28716802,"Posted: 27 December, 2016",all,jester,"Just bought this game and played 4.5 hours straight. The ship building is really addicting. It's awesome how you have to balance your thrusters, weapons, modules and how it looks. It seems incredibly balanced. Except for the fact that the guns are ridicolously strong. But since this game supports workshop, and I see other players having around the 100-1000 hours played area, I'm sure you can probably fix most stuff you don't like with a mod. I would probably pay the full price it's asking for this game (I paid 50%).20 Hours played: Well, the ship building is still as addicting as when I first started playing this game. It's so cool to kinda understand ship design stuff when designing your own ships. For instance, you realise your front is very vulnerable and you add more armor to the front of the ship. But since you want to keep the total mass down, and you realise you don't need all that armor in the back of the ship, you get an old school design where the back is your weakness. And all the games where you have to take something down and the game tells you to shoot it's back for more damage suddenly makes sense.Another example is maneuverability vs armor vs damage. You want your ship to have massive amounts of armor, and you want a ton of guns on your ship. But you dont have any space for thrusters. So your ship can't move. You take away some guns and make room for thrusters, but you have too few and too small thrusters to move your big ship. You take away even more guns to an ""acceptable"" point, and you put in more thrusters, but your ship still moves super  sluggish. You redesign the whole ship and make sure you worry about how it moves at all times. But the bigger your ship becomes, the harder it is to find enough spots to fit your thrusters. Makes you understand why big ships are always portrayed as super slow moving. Amazingly fun tinkering in any case!"
